sql:
SELECT COUNT(trial_id) 
FROM trials 
WHERE trial_id NOT IN (SELECT trial_id FROM corrections);

SELECT name
FROM participants
WHERE consent_date = (SELECT MAX(consent_date) FROM participants);

external_knowledge:
- "Blossomed" refers to the trials that have an average reaction time greater than 500 milliseconds;
- "Vast garden of experimental trials" is a metaphor for the database containing various trial types;
- "Completed and processed" means the sessions have a status of 'completed' and the trials have been processed;
- "Unique sessions" refers to the number of distinct sessions in which the trials were conducted.

- 'gardeners' refers to participants;
- 'in their prime (ages 18 to 65)' refers to the age range of 18 to 65;
- 'tended to more than 5 flowers' refers to having completed more than 5 trials;
- 'types of flowers' refers to trial types;
- 'average bloom number' refers to the average trial number;
- 'total flowers tended to' refers to the total number of trials;
- 'sessions that have come to a full bloom' refers to sessions with a status of 'Completed'.

- 'Participant performance metrics' include average reaction time, total correct responses, and total incorrect responses;
- 'Session performance metrics' include the total number of correct and incorrect trials in the session;
- 'Trial order' is the sequence of trials within a session.

- "seeds have sprouted" refers to the total number of trials conducted;
- "garden of participation" refers to the database containing participants, sessions, and trials;
- "each participant has planted multiple sessions" means each participant is associated with multiple sessions;
- "each session has multiple trials" means each session is associated with multiple trials.

- "Slowest average reaction time" refers to the highest average reaction time among all participants;
- The reaction time is measured in milliseconds;
- The average reaction time is calculated by dividing the total reaction time by the total number of sessions.

- "quickest reflexes" refers to the lowest average reaction time;
- "top 3 participants" means the participants with the fastest reaction times;
- "trial types" are different categories or types of trials.

- 'Top participants' refers to those ranked first in their respective sessions;
- 'Accuracy rate' is calculated as the number of accurate responses divided by the total number of trials;
- 'Multiple trials' means more than one trial.
